00:19:12.120 --> 00:19:14.110
&gt;&gt;Marisa: Very cool. Okay.

00:19:14.110 --> 00:19:20.050
&gt;&gt;male #1: This is sort of two halves of the
same question. One is you said 90 percent

00:19:20.050 --> 00:19:26.700
of these deaths are preventable. What are
some of the key remediations, the key things

00:19:26.700 --> 00:19:34.270
to fix? And the second one is, I just imagine
that in most, many of these circumstances,

00:19:34.270 --> 00:19:39.600
isn't it really because of the power imbalance
of women do the work and well I don't know

00:19:39.600 --> 00:19:41.470
what the men do?

00:19:41.470 --> 00:19:42.470
[laughter]

00:19:42.470 --> 00:19:48.100
&gt;&gt;Christy Turlington: Well the most important
thing is really prevention. So the importance

00:19:48.100 --> 00:19:55.690
of family planning is tremendous. That ties
into education. So education is also incredibly

00:19:55.690 --> 00:20:03.810
important. When a girl has more than a primary
education she will just instinctively delay

00:20:03.810 --> 00:20:11.140
a first pregnancy, marriage. She'll understand
better to space pregnancies. That will save

00:20:11.140 --> 00:20:17.680
her life just by virtue of holding off starting
a family.

00:20:17.680 --> 00:20:24.580
Secondly, oh and then obviously having the
ability to control your fertility is tremendously

00:20:24.580 --> 00:20:31.580
empowering and incredibly important. So many
women who are pregnant and at a ridiculous

00:20:31.580 --> 00:20:37.950
age like 13 or 14 for the first time in much
of Sub-Saharan African and Southeast Asia

00:20:37.950 --> 00:20:44.690
-- they have not chosen to be pregnant. They've
not chosen to have sex. So education and working

00:20:44.690 --> 00:20:52.420
on that prevention piece and how to empower
girls to protect their own bodies is a critical

00:20:52.420 --> 00:20:53.420
piece.

00:20:53.420 --> 00:20:57.070
But then the health care worker piece is also
really important. We will never have enough

00:20:57.070 --> 00:21:02.630
doctors to fulfill the burden of most global
health issues. And as you heard our obstetrician

00:21:02.630 --> 00:21:08.750
in Tanzania say, he was the only OB for 2.5
million people. Well 2.5 million people were

00:21:08.750 --> 00:21:13.090
not seeking care from a doctor because they
don't even think about seeing a doctor in

00:21:13.090 --> 00:21:19.740
their daily lives. But when a woman is pregnant,
that's an opportunity for a woman to be seen

00:21:19.740 --> 00:21:23.470
for the first time. And there are tremendous
things being done with not just community

00:21:23.470 --> 00:21:27.360
health workers but midwives and nurses and
midlevel providers.

00:21:27.360 --> 00:21:33.190
In Tanzania, the teenager that you see at
the end -- she had a C-section in the end

00:21:33.190 --> 00:21:37.570
but by an AMO which is the equivalent of a
physician's assistant. And that's who's doing

00:21:37.570 --> 00:21:44.310
the majority of the cesarean sections in Sub-Saharan
Africa, and midwives are doing 'em too actually.

00:21:44.310 --> 00:21:49.920
So I would say the skilled birth attendants,
the prevention piece being the family planning

00:21:49.920 --> 00:21:53.010
and contraception, and education.

00:21:53.010 --> 00:21:58.849
&gt;&gt;female #1: I wanted to thank you so much
I mean I thought the film was great and I

00:21:58.849 --> 00:22:05.370
really liked the tone of it. I had worked
in Tanzania a bit before and I liked sort

00:22:05.370 --> 00:22:10.300
of the just non-intrusive, I guess, narration.
It just sort of felt like you were letting

00:22:10.300 --> 00:22:14.750
the people there interact the way that you
would observe it.

00:22:14.750 --> 00:22:21.380
I was curious about the diagnosis the nurse
kept giving some of the patients about their

00:22:21.380 --> 00:22:26.860
pelvis bone. So is that linked to I mean is
that a common thing? Is it linked to maybe

00:22:26.860 --> 00:22:31.950
being young or is it something with the Maasai
or what was the issue there?

00:22:31.950 --> 00:22:35.920
&gt;&gt;Christy Turlington: That's a good question.
It is linked to being too young but also malnutrition

00:22:35.920 --> 00:22:36.920
and nutrition --

00:22:36.920 --> 00:22:37.920
&gt;&gt;female #1: Okay.

00:22:37.920 --> 00:22:42.190
&gt;&gt;Christy Turlington: is a huge factor too.
So these poor women -- they tend to eat last

00:22:42.190 --> 00:22:46.370
even when they're pregnant. If they're very
young when they start having a baby, they

00:22:46.370 --> 00:22:51.540
don't develop properly. I mean even women
that are older, you just see their stature

00:22:51.540 --> 00:22:56.400
as very tiny. And so that was a common I mean
in the amount of time we were in that clinic

00:22:56.400 --> 00:23:00.640
that was commonly the reason why a woman had
to be referred. And what happens is if she's

00:23:00.640 --> 00:23:05.370
not developed enough and her pelvis is small,
then she's a candidate for an obstructed labor

00:23:05.370 --> 00:23:11.360
which in most scenarios ends up where the
baby dies. But in many cases, the woman will

00:23:11.360 --> 00:23:16.640
die also and at the very least she'll suffer
a complication, a morbidity which could last

00:23:16.640 --> 00:23:22.000
her a lifetime like an obstructed fistula
which is a horrible, horrible handicap --

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:23.000
&gt;&gt;female #1: Um-hum.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:24.000
&gt;&gt;Christy Turlington: that so many women have.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:25.000
&gt;&gt;female #1: Okay. Thank you.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:26.600
&gt;&gt;Christy Turlington: Thank you for the question.

00:23:26.600 --> 00:23:29.360
